<exercise checkit-seed="0024" checkit-slug="M1" checkit-title="Multiplying matrices">
  <statement>
    <p>Of the following three matrices, only two may be multiplied.
      <md><mrow>A= \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
-2 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 &amp; -2
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; B= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \\
-2 &amp; 1 &amp; 6 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
-3 &amp; -3 &amp; 3
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; C= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 &amp; -2 &amp; -2 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0
\end{array}\right] </mrow></md>
      Explain which two can be multiplied and why. Then show how to find their product.</p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <me>AB= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-6 &amp; -7 &amp; 4 \\
7 &amp; 6 &amp; -8
\end{array}\right] </me>
  </answer>
</exercise>

